Instead, opposition to the coup was based on the illegality of the principle of usurping power and widespread fear that if Gorbachev could be rolled up, then other democratically elected leaders could be, too. ; He lost by being peripheral to what happened. ; One result of the bungled coup is that Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev -- even though reinstated as head of state -- could be irrelevant to what happens next, analysts said. As soon as the hard-liners made their move Sunday night -- two days beforeGorbachev was to sign the treaty -- it was obvious the coup was doomed to failure, they said. 